---
import BaseLayout from '../../layouts/BaseLayout.astro';
import '../../styles/global.css';
import '../../styles/course.css';
import LessonPage from '../../components/course/LessonPage';
import GatePanel from '../../components/assessment/GatePanel';
---

<BaseLayout title="Case Study: Reading a Dense Gemma Block">
  <LessonPage lessonId="L39" client:load>

    <div class="lesson-section">
      <div class="section-label">Question</div>
      <div class="lesson-question">What does a dense Gemma block look like in real code?</div>
    </div>

    <div class="lesson-section">
      <div class="section-label">Intuition</div>
      <p>
        You have learned every concept individually: RMSNorm, attention, residual connections, FFN. Now it is time to see them assembled in one place. The Gemma model builder in <code>llama.cpp</code> constructs a single transformer block in a straightforward sequence, and every line maps to a concept you already know.
      </p>
      <p>
        A dense Gemma block follows the pre-norm transformer pattern exactly:
      </p>
      <ol style="list-style: decimal; padding-left: var(--space-5); margin: var(--space-3) 0;">
        <li style="padding: var(--space-1) 0; font-size: var(--text-sm); color: var(--ink-secondary);">
          <strong style="color: var(--ink-primary);">RMSNorm</strong> the hidden states (attention pre-norm)
        </li>
        <li style="padding: var(--space-1) 0; font-size: var(--text-sm); color: var(--ink-secondary);">
          <strong style="color: var(--sem-attention);">Self-attention</strong> &mdash; Q, K, V projections, scaled dot-product, output projection
        </li>
        <li style="padding: var(--space-1) 0; font-size: var(--text-sm); color: var(--ink-secondary);">
          <strong style="color: var(--ink-primary);">Residual add</strong> &mdash; add attention output back to the input
        </li>
        <li style="padding: var(--space-1) 0; font-size: var(--text-sm); color: var(--ink-secondary);">
          <strong style="color: var(--ink-primary);">RMSNorm</strong> the result (FFN pre-norm)
        </li>
        <li style="padding: var(--space-1) 0; font-size: var(--text-sm); color: var(--ink-secondary);">
          <strong style="color: var(--sem-ffn);">Feed-forward network</strong> &mdash; gate projection, up projection, activation, down projection
        </li>
        <li style="padding: var(--space-1) 0; font-size: var(--text-sm); color: var(--ink-secondary);">
          <strong style="color: var(--ink-primary);">Residual add</strong> &mdash; add FFN output back to the post-attention residual
        </li>
      </ol>
      <p>
        That is the entire block. No surprises, no hidden steps. The builder code reads almost like pseudocode because each call corresponds directly to the mathematical operation it implements.
      </p>
    </div>

    <div class="lesson-section">
      <div class="section-label">Toy Example</div>
      <div class="toy-example">
        <p style="font-size: var(--text-sm); color: var(--ink-tertiary); margin-bottom: var(--space-3);">
          Tracing one token's hidden state through a single dense Gemma block:
        </p>
        <div style="font-family: var(--font-mono); font-size: var(--text-sm);">
          <div style="margin-bottom: var(--space-2);">
            <span style="color: var(--ink-ghost);">input:</span> x = [0.5, &minus;1.2, 0.8, 2.1]
          </div>
          <div style="padding-left: var(--space-4); border-left: 2px solid var(--sem-attention-dim); margin-bottom: var(--space-2);">
            <span style="color: var(--ink-ghost);">phase 1:</span> x_norm = RMSNorm(x)
          </div>
          <div style="padding-left: var(--space-4); border-left: 2px solid var(--sem-attention-dim); margin-bottom: var(--space-2);">
            <span style="color: var(--sem-attention);">phase 2:</span> attn_out = self_attention(x_norm)
          </div>
          <div style="margin-bottom: var(--space-2);">
            <span style="color: var(--ink-ghost);">phase 3:</span> r1 = x + attn_out &nbsp; <span style="color: var(--ink-tertiary);">(residual)</span>
          </div>
          <div style="padding-left: var(--space-4); border-left: 2px solid var(--sem-ffn-dim); margin-bottom: var(--space-2);">
            <span style="color: var(--ink-ghost);">phase 4:</span> r1_norm = RMSNorm(r1)
          </div>
          <div style="padding-left: var(--space-4); border-left: 2px solid var(--sem-ffn-dim); margin-bottom: var(--space-2);">
            <span style="color: var(--sem-ffn);">phase 5:</span> ffn_out = FFN(r1_norm)
          </div>
          <div>
            <span style="color: var(--ink-ghost);">phase 6:</span> output = r1 + ffn_out &nbsp; <span style="color: var(--ink-tertiary);">(residual)</span>
          </div>
        </div>
        <p style="font-size: var(--text-sm); color: var(--ink-tertiary); margin-top: var(--space-3);">
          Two sub-blocks (attention, FFN), each wrapped in norm-then-residual. This is all a dense block does.
        </p>
      </div>
    </div>

    <div class="lesson-section">
      <div class="section-label">Shapes</div>
      <div class="shape-card">
        <div>Input: [n_tokens, d_model]</div>
        <div>After attention pre-norm: [n_tokens, d_model]</div>
        <div>After attention + residual: [n_tokens, d_model]</div>
        <div>After FFN pre-norm: [n_tokens, d_model]</div>
        <div>After FFN + residual: [n_tokens, d_model]</div>
        <div style="color: var(--ink-tertiary); margin-top: var(--space-2);">Shape is preserved at every stage. Only the values change.</div>
      </div>
    </div>

    <div class="lesson-section">
      <div class="section-label">Math</div>
      <p>The complete dense block in one formula chain:</p>
      <div style="font-family: var(--font-mono); font-size: var(--text-sm); background: var(--surface-3); padding: var(--space-3) var(--space-4); border-radius: var(--radius-sm); margin: var(--space-3) 0;">
        <div style="color: var(--sem-attention);">h' = x + attention(RMSNorm(x))</div>
        <div style="color: var(--sem-ffn);">h'' = h' + FFN(RMSNorm(h'))</div>
        <div style="color: var(--ink-tertiary); margin-top: var(--space-2);">Two residual sub-blocks. Norm before each transform. That is the entire layer.</div>
      </div>
    </div>

    <div class="lesson-section">
      <div class="section-label">The Real Code</div>
      <p>
        Here is the actual layer loop from <code>src/models/gemma.cpp</code> in llama.cpp. This is not pseudocode — it is the builder that constructs the computation graph for one dense Gemma block, repeated for every layer. Read it line by line and match each call to the six phases above.
      </p>
      <div style="background: var(--surface-3); border-radius: var(--radius-md); padding: var(--space-4); margin: var(--space-4) 0; overflow-x: auto;">
        <pre style="font-family: var(--font-mono); font-size: var(--text-xs); line-height: 1.7; margin: 0; color: var(--ink-secondary);" set:html={`<code><span style="color: var(--ink-ghost);">for (int il = 0; il &lt; n_layer; ++il) {</span>

    <span style="color: var(--ink-primary);">// Phase 1: attention pre-norm</span>
    cur = <span style="color: var(--sem-attention);">build_norm</span>(inpL,
            model.layers[il].attn_norm, NULL,
            LLM_NORM_RMS, il);

    <span style="color: var(--ink-primary);">// Phase 2: self-attention (Q, K, V projections &rarr; RoPE &rarr; attention &rarr; output projection)</span>
    {
        ggml_tensor * Qcur = <span style="color: var(--sem-attention);">build_lora_mm</span>(model.layers[il].wq, cur);
        ggml_tensor * Kcur = <span style="color: var(--sem-attention);">build_lora_mm</span>(model.layers[il].wk, cur);
        ggml_tensor * Vcur = <span style="color: var(--sem-attention);">build_lora_mm</span>(model.layers[il].wv, cur);

        <span style="color: var(--ink-ghost);">// ... reshape to heads, apply RoPE, scale queries ...</span>

        cur = <span style="color: var(--sem-attention);">build_attn</span>(inp_attn,
                model.layers[il].wo, NULL,
                Qcur, Kcur, Vcur, nullptr, nullptr, nullptr, 1.0f, il);
    }

    <span style="color: var(--ink-primary);">// Phase 3: residual add (attention output + input)</span>
    ggml_tensor * sa_out = <span style="color: var(--sem-token);">ggml_add</span>(ctx0, cur, inpL);

    <span style="color: var(--ink-primary);">// Phase 4: FFN pre-norm</span>
    cur = <span style="color: var(--sem-ffn);">build_norm</span>(sa_out,
            model.layers[il].ffn_norm, NULL,
            LLM_NORM_RMS, il);

    <span style="color: var(--ink-primary);">// Phase 5: feed-forward network (gate, up, down projections)</span>
    {
        cur = <span style="color: var(--sem-ffn);">build_ffn</span>(cur,
                model.layers[il].ffn_up,   NULL, NULL,
                model.layers[il].ffn_gate, NULL, NULL,
                model.layers[il].ffn_down, NULL, NULL,
                NULL,
                LLM_FFN_GELU, LLM_FFN_PAR, il);
    }

    <span style="color: var(--ink-primary);">// Phase 6: residual add (FFN output + post-attention residual)</span>
    cur = <span style="color: var(--sem-token);">ggml_add</span>(ctx0, cur, sa_out);

    inpL = cur;  <span style="color: var(--ink-ghost);">// output becomes next layer's input</span>
<span style="color: var(--ink-ghost);">}</span></code>`} />
      </div>
      <p style="font-size: var(--text-xs); color: var(--ink-ghost); margin-top: var(--space-2);">
        Source: ggml-org/llama.cpp @ <code>94ca829b</code> &mdash; <code>src/models/gemma.cpp</code>. The actual code may have changed since this snapshot.
      </p>
      <p style="font-size: var(--text-sm); color: var(--ink-secondary); margin-top: var(--space-3);">
        Notice: there is no magic. <code>build_norm</code> applies RMSNorm. <code>build_lora_mm</code> runs a matrix multiply (the Q, K, V projections). <code>build_attn</code> runs the full attention mechanism. <code>build_ffn</code> runs the gated feed-forward network. <code>ggml_add</code> is the residual connection. The six phases from the Intuition section above map directly onto these function calls.
      </p>
    </div>

    <div class="lesson-section">
      <div class="section-label">Implementation Hook</div>
      <div class="impl-hook">
        <p style="font-size: var(--text-sm); color: var(--ink-secondary);">
          The code above is from the Gemma model builder. Each model file in <code>src/models/</code> constructs its architecture by calling shared helpers from <code>src/llama-graph.cpp</code>. The helpers (<code>build_norm</code>, <code>build_attn</code>, <code>build_ffn</code>) are reused across all model architectures — what changes between models is which helpers are called and in what order.
        </p>
        <div class="file-path"><a href="https://github.com/ggml-org/llama.cpp/blob/94ca829b6001019622c0f67fcd48e9ec6bd7dce8/src/models/gemma.cpp#L22" target="_blank" rel="noopener">src/models/gemma.cpp — layer loop (L22)</a></div>
      </div>
    </div>

    <div class="lesson-section">
      <div class="section-label">Performance Hook</div>
      <div class="perf-hook">
        <p style="font-size: var(--text-sm); color: var(--ink-secondary);">
          In a dense block, all tokens pass through every parameter. The attention phase cost scales with sequence length (token-to-token interactions), while the FFN phase cost is fixed per token regardless of sequence length. During prefill with long contexts, attention compute dominates. During single-token decode, FFN projections account for most of the per-token FLOPs because there is only one query token — though attention still contributes memory traffic from reading the KV cache.
        </p>
      </div>
    </div>

    <div class="lesson-section">
      <div class="section-label">Check Yourself</div>
      <GatePanel
        client:load
        lessonId="L39"
        gateStrength="hard"
        questions={[
          {
            id: 'L39-q1',
            type: 'single_choice',
            prompt: 'What are the six phases of a dense Gemma block, in order?',
            tag: 'conceptual',
            choices: [
              { id: 'a', text: 'Attention, norm, residual, FFN, norm, residual', isCorrect: false },
              { id: 'b', text: 'Norm, attention, residual, norm, FFN, residual', isCorrect: true },
              { id: 'c', text: 'Norm, FFN, residual, norm, attention, residual', isCorrect: false },
            ],
            explanation: 'A pre-norm dense block follows: RMSNorm → attention → residual add → RMSNorm → FFN → residual add. The norm always comes before the transform, and each sub-block ends with a residual connection.',
          },
          {
            id: 'L39-q2',
            type: 'single_choice',
            prompt: 'Why does the builder call build_norm() twice per layer?',
            tag: 'conceptual',
            choices: [
              { id: 'a', text: 'One normalizes the attention weights, the other normalizes the FFN weights', isCorrect: false },
              { id: 'b', text: 'One is the attention pre-norm, the other is the FFN pre-norm — each sub-block gets its own normalization', isCorrect: true },
              { id: 'c', text: 'The second call is a post-norm applied after the entire block', isCorrect: false },
            ],
            explanation: 'In a pre-norm transformer, each sub-block (attention and FFN) has its own RMSNorm applied before the transform. This means build_norm() is called once before build_attn() and once before build_ffn().',
          },
          {
            id: 'L39-q3',
            type: 'single_choice',
            prompt: 'What is the residual connection doing in each sub-block?',
            tag: 'conceptual',
            choices: [
              { id: 'a', text: 'Replacing the input with the transformed output', isCorrect: false },
              { id: 'b', text: 'Concatenating the input and output to double the dimension', isCorrect: false },
              { id: 'c', text: 'Adding the sub-block output back to its input, so the layer only needs to learn the change', isCorrect: true },
            ],
            explanation: 'The residual connection adds the transform output to its original input. The sub-block learns a delta — what to add — rather than a complete new representation. This preserves information and stabilizes training.',
          },
        ]}
      />
    </div>

  </LessonPage>
</BaseLayout>
